yes/no|2007|04|21}}<ref name=\"DG 1\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.dublinglobe.com/community/big-reads/mike-feerick-meaningful-career-internet-since-1991 |title=Mike Feerick: a Meaningful Career on the Internet since 1991 |last=Bushnell |first=Niam |date=16 March 2017 |website=Dublin Globe |language=en-GB |access-date=6 January 2019}}</ref>\n| revenue              = \n| alexa                = {{DecreasePositive}}<!-- {{Steady}} {{DecreasePositive}} -->5,564<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.alexa.com/siteinfo/alison.com |title=Alison.com Traffic, Demographics and Competitors - Alexa |date=11 April 2020 |website=[[Alexa Internet]] |access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n| ip                   = \n| issn                 = <!-- ISSN, e.g. 1085-6706 (automatically linked to https://www.WorldCat.org) -->\n| eissn                = <!-- eISSN, e.g. 1085-6706 (automatically linked to https://www.WorldCat.org) -->\n| oclc                 = <!-- OCLC number, useful where an ISSN has not been allocated (automatically linked to https://www.WorldCat.org) -->\n| current_status       = Active\n| footnotes            = \n}}\n'''Alison''' is a free [[e-learning|online education platform]] that mostly focuses on workplace-based skills.<ref name=\"NYT 1\"/> It was founded in [[Galway]], [[Ireland]] by Irish [[social entrepreneur]] [[Mike Feerick]] on 21 April 2007.<ref name=\"Wired\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.wiredacademic.com/2011/09/khan-academy-competitor-mike-feerick-of-alison-com-talks-about-future-of-online-education/#sthash.bQYwAbYq.dpuf |title=Khan Academy Competitor? Mike Feerick of Alison.com Talks About The Future Of Online Education |last=Glader |first=Paul |website=Wired Academic |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130531031705/http://www.wiredacademic.com/2011/09/khan-academy-competitor-mike-feerick-of-alison-com-talks-about-future-of-online-education/#sthash.bQYwAbYq.dpuf |archive-date=31 May 2013 |url-status=dead |access-date=25 July 2013}}</ref>\n\nIt has 14 million registered learners, 2 million graduates and 1,500 courses available for free access in March 2020.<ref name=\"Connacht Tribune\">{{Cite web |url=https://connachttribune.ie/global-online-education-is-thriving-from-galway-through-turbulent-times-121/ |title=Global online education is thriving from Galway through turbulent times |date=March 26, 2020 |website=[[Connacht Tribune]] |language=en-US |access-date=March 31, 2020}}</ref> Alison's learners have access to online courses, specializations, and degrees in a variety of subjects published by many big name universities and organizations.\n\n==Background==\n===History and development===\nIn 2005, while server and broadband costs were decreasing and webpages were becoming more monetizable, [[Mike Feerick]] realized that free education could be provided online as a scalable business. In 2006, Feerick developed the platform and designed it. On 21 April 2007, Alison was launched with its first free customer and six courses.<ref name=\"Wired\"/> Among Alison's stated aims are to drive all costs of accessing digitally-based education and skills training to zero and to bring [[disruptive innovation]] to global education and skills training through a scalable business model which enables registered users to be educated for free.<ref name=\"Wired\"/> In April 2017, the company decided to make a technical overhaul of the platform. The company also launched its mobile application, which drives 50% of the website's traffic worldwide.<ref name=\"Forbes 1\"/><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.careerindia.com/news/nsdc-alison-collaborate-skill-development-across-india-017690.html |title=NSDC and Alison collaborate for skill development across India |last=Malapur |first=Deepak |date=18 July 2016 |website=Career India |language=en |access-date=13 January 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"RTE\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.rte.ie/news/business/2016/0715/802576-alison-deal-in-india/ |title=Alison announces new partnership in India |date=15 July 2016 |website=[[RTE.ie]] |language=en |access-date=13 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Product and services==\n===Business model===\nAlison income is generated from advertising and sales of certificates. According to ''[[The Economist]]'', the company seeks to drive education through advertising in the manner of television and radio. Through the [[pay per click|online pay per click advertising revenue]] model, Alison has founded a business model it can provide learning materials at no cost to the learner.{{according to whom|date=January 2019}}<ref name=\"Wired\"/><ref name=\"The Economist 1\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.economist.com/business/2013/07/20/the-attack-of-the-moocs |title=The attack of the MOOCs |date=20 July 2013 |website=[[The Economist]] |access-date=6 January 2019}}</ref> It aims to make learning accessible to blue collar or \"bottom of the pyramid\" learners.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://alison.com/publish/bottom-of-the-pyramid-learning |title=Bottom of the Pyramid Learning |website=Alison |access-date=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Courses===\nAlison currently offers more than a thousand courses at certificate, diploma, and learning path levels across nine core subject categories. The certificate level courses require two to three hours of study while the more rigorous diploma level courses require ten to fifteen hours of study.<ref name=\"Alison 1\">{{Cite web |url=https://alison.com/about/about-alison-courses |title=Understand the types of courses offered by Alison |website=Alison |language=en |access-date=6 January 2019}}</ref> There is no time limit for completing a course.<ref name=\"Forbes 2\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/peterhigh/2015/07/21/ceo-of-the-worlds-first-mooc-provides-hope-to-former-prisoners-through-education/ |title=CEO Of The World's First MOOC Provides Hope To Former Prisoners Through Education |last=High |first=Peter |date=11 July 2010 |website=[[Forbes]] |language=en |access-date=6 January 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Wired\"/> One of Alison's courses is ABC IT, a fifteen to twenty-hour training suite which is cited by ''[[The New York Times]]'' as \"covering similar ground\" to the [[International Computer Driving License]] without the cost of certification.<ref name=\"NYT 1\"/> In 2020, Alison published a course on the [[COVID-19|coronavirus]] and translated it into more than 50 languages.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://alison.com/coronavirus |title=Coronavirus - What you need to know |website=Alison |access-date=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Accreditation===\nAccording to the Alison website, Alison is not currently accredited by any external body, and does not intend to be accredited at any time in the future, <ref>https://alison.com/faqs/search?search=Acrediation/are-alison-courses-recognised-or-accredited</ref> while delivering courses with up-to-date international pedagogical standards.<ref>https://alison.com/about/accreditation</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nAlison was among the four winners of the 2010 [[UNESCO King Hamad bin Isa Al Khalifa Prize]], a Prize for innovation in ICT for Education.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.advertiser.ie/galway/article/35436/galway-based-online-learning-provider-wins-top-unesco-prize |title=Galway-based online learning provider wins top UNESCO prize |date=20 January 2011 |website=[[Galway Advertiser]] |access-date=19 January 2011}}</ref> In October 2013, Alison won an award at the [[World Innovation Summit for Education]] held in [[Qatar]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-24711245 |title=Biggest educator you've never heard of |last=Coughlan |first=Sean |date=30 October 2013 |website=[[BBC News]] |language=en-GB |access-date=7 January 2019}}</ref>  Since 2013 Alison courses have become generally recognized by many employers, particularly in occupations and disciplines where no external certification by professional bodies post-graduation exist.  It is estimated that currently over 1.5 million people around the world have an Alison course on their CV.\n\nDavid Bornstein of ''The New York Times'' noted that 'practical skills training is usually expensive.'<ref name=\"NYT 1\"/> Initially some observers also predicted the ineffectiveness of the [[Massive open online course|MOOC]] model in delivering real educational impact, highlighting the lack of personal interaction with educators and the high drop-out rate of users with no incentive to commit without any material investment of their own.<ref name=\"SLATE\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.slate.com/articles/technology/future_tense/2013/07/moocs_could_be_disastrous_for_students_and_professors.html |title=The MOOC Racket |last=Rees |first=Jonathan |date=23 July 2013 |website=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]] |access-date=29 July 2013}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Language education]]\n* [[List of Language Self-Study Programs]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://alison.com/}}\n\n{{MOOC}}\n\n[[Category:Irish educational websites]]\n[[Category:Education companies established in 2007]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 2007]]\n[[Category:Education companies of Ireland]]\n[[Category:Distance education institutions based in the Republic of Ireland]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Free online education platform}}\n{{Infobox website\n| name                 = Alison\n| logo                 = Alison-logo-wikipedia.png\n| logo_size            = \n| logo_alt             = \n| logo_caption         = <!-- or: | logocaption = -->\n| screenshot           = \n| collapsible          = <!-- set as \"on\", \"y\", etc, otherwise omit/leave blank -->\n| collapsetext         = <!-- collapsible area's heading (default \"Screenshot\"); omit/leave blank if collapsible not set -->\n| background           = <!-- for collapsetext heading; default grey (gainsboro) -->\n| screenshot_size      = 320px\n| screenshot_alt       = \n| caption              = Screenshot of Alison.com's webpage.\n| url                  = {{URL|www.alison.com}}\n| areas                = \n| location             = [[Galway]], [[Ireland]]\n| commercial           = Yes\n| type                 = [[e-learning]], [[online education]]\n| registration         = Required\n| language             = [[English language|English]], [[Spanish language|Spanish]], [[French language|French]], [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]], [[Russian language|Russian]]. [[Arabic]], [[Chinese language|Chinese]], [[Hindi language|Hindi]], [[Urdu language|Urdu]]<ref name=\"NYT 1\">{{Cite web|type=editorial |url=https://opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/07/11/open-education-for-a-global-economy/ |title=Open Education for a Global Economy |last=Bornstein |first=David |date=11 July 2012 |website=[[The New York Times]] |language=en-US |access-date=6 January 2019}}</ref>\n| num_users            = 11 million <small>(2017)</small><ref name=\"Forbes 1\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/peterhigh/2017/12/11/is-alison-the-answer-to-the-worlds-education-needs/ |title=Is Alison The Answer To The World's Education Needs? |last=High |first=Peter |date=11 December 2017 |website=[[Forbes]] |language=en |access-date=6 January 2019}}</ref>\n| content_license      = <!-- or: | content_licence = -->\n| programming_language = \n| owner                = Capernaum Ltd.\n| creator              = [[Mike Feerick]] <small>(founder and [[CEO]])</small>\n| editor               = <!-- or: | editors = -->\n| launch_date          = {{Start date and age|df=yes/no|2007|04|21}}<ref name=\"DG 1\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.dublinglobe.com/community/big-reads/mike-feerick-meaningful-career-internet-since-1991 |title=Mike Feerick: a Meaningful Career on the Internet since 1991 |last=Bushnell |first=Niam |date=16 March 2017 |website=Dublin Globe |language=en-GB |access-date=6 January 2019}}</ref>\n| revenue              = \n| alexa                = {{DecreasePositive}}<!-- {{Steady}} {{DecreasePositive}} -->6,315<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.alexa.com/siteinfo/alison.com |title=